From e7ae357468e076a45e34729bacd01e97adfedc68 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Firo Yang <fyang@suse.com>
Date: Sat, 29 Dec 2018 05:27:19 +0100
Subject: [PATCH 1/1] net: ipsec: fix a kernel oops caused by reentrant
 workqueue

Patch-mainline: Never, since kernel 3.6, all workqueues are non-reentrant;
		and the oldest longterm support kernel is 3.16; so
		upsteam doesn't need this patch.
References: bsc#1119314

Due to the reentrant workqueue, system_wq in our case, it's possible to
parallelly queue more than 2 xfrm_hash_resize works to system_wq.
If this happens for several times, the state_hmask will be go beyond
the xfrm_state_hashmax.

BTW, this issue was revealed by a kernel oops; the reason for this kernel
oops is that when state_hmask goes to be a number large than maximum value
of int, state_hmask will be truncated to 0 when nsize is passed
to xfrm_hash_alloc() in xfrm_hash_resize().

To fix all of these two problems, just add a double check in
xfrm_hash_resize().

Credit to enginners from ericsson.com for reporting and identifying and
testing this issue.

Signed-off-by: Firo Yang <fyang@suse.com>
---
 net/xfrm/xfrm_state.c | 3 +++
 1 file changed, 3 insertions(+)

diff --git a/net/xfrm/xfrm_state.c b/net/xfrm/xfrm_state.c
index 9414b9c..c230901 100644
--- a/net/xfrm/xfrm_state.c
+++ b/net/xfrm/xfrm_state.c
@@ -114,6 +114,9 @@ static void xfrm_hash_resize(struct work_struct *work)
 
 	mutex_lock(&hash_resize_mutex);
 
+	if ((net->xfrm.state_hmask + 1) >= xfrm_state_hashmax)
+		goto out_unlock;
+
 	nsize = xfrm_hash_new_size(net->xfrm.state_hmask);
 	ndst = xfrm_hash_alloc(nsize);
 	if (!ndst)
